INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '0257a825-fac8-4fb2-98c4-6b1a49dc8125',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$vitest Testing Pyramid — What to Test at Every Layer$escape$,
  $escape$Vitest sits at the unit and integration layers of the pyramid; Playwright owns E2E. Misplacing tests is the most expensive mistake in a frontend test suite.

Unit tests (the wide base): pure functions, hooks in isolation via `renderHook`, and Zod schemas. Use `vi.fn()` to stub dependencies. Keep them sub-10ms — vitest's thread-pool makes this trivial.

Integration tests (the middle): render a real component tree with `@testing-library/react`, but mock the network with `vi.mock('~/lib/api')` or intercept via `msw` handlers loaded in `setupFiles`. These validate that components wire props, state, and callbacks correctly without a browser.

E2E tests (the narrow tip): let Playwright own this. Only cover critical user journeys — auth flow, checkout, form submission. Never duplicate in vitest what Playwright already asserts.

The forcing function: if a vitest test requires a browser API (`window.matchMedia`, `IntersectionObserver`), either mock it in `setupFiles` or reconsider whether it belongs in Playwright. Leaking browser-specific concerns into vitest slows the suite and signals a layer violation.$escape$,
  $escape$// vitest.setup.ts — mock browser APIs once, globally
import { vi } from 'vitest'

Object.defineProperty(window, 'matchMedia', {
  writable: true,
  value: vi.fn().mockImplementation((query: string) => ({
    matches: false,
    media: query,
    addEventListener: vi.fn(),
    removeEventListener: vi.fn(),
  })),
})

// unit test — pure function, zero ceremony
import { describe, it, expect } from 'vitest'
import { formatBytes } from './formatBytes'

describe('formatBytes', () => {
  it('converts 1024 to 1 KB', () => {
    expect(formatBytes(1024)).toBe('1 KB')
  })
})$escape$,
