INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'd274cdf4-514c-48c8-92e0-48ce17006691',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$vitest Test Data Management — Factories, Fixtures, and test.extend()$escape$,
  $escape$Hard-coded objects scattered across test files break silently when shapes change. The fix: factory functions paired with vitest's first-class fixture system.

A factory is a plain function that returns a valid object with sane defaults, accepting partial overrides. TypeScript's `Partial<T>` keeps it type-safe without forcing callers to specify every field.

For stateful setup — DB rows, auth sessions, pre-populated stores — use `test.extend()`. It lets you declare typed fixtures that are constructed before each test and torn down after, with full async support. Each fixture receives already-resolved peer fixtures, so you can compose them: an `authedClient` fixture can depend on a `user` fixture. Vitest handles the dependency graph.

Avoid `beforeEach` for complex seeding; it bleeds state implicitly across every test in the suite. `test.extend()` makes dependencies explicit and co-located with the tests that need them.

For shared read-only data (enum-like constants, static API responses), use module-level `const` — no fixture overhead needed. Reserve fixtures for anything that mutates or needs isolation.$escape$,
  $escape$import { test, expect } from 'vitest'

type User = { id: string; name: string; role: 'admin' | 'viewer' }

const createUser = (overrides: Partial<User> = {}): User => ({
  id: crypto.randomUUID(),
  name: 'Alice',
  role: 'viewer',
  ...overrides,
})

const myTest = test.extend<{ adminUser: User }>({
  adminUser: async ({}, use) => {
    await use(createUser({ role: 'admin' }))
    // teardown: db.delete(user.id) etc.
  },
})

myTest('admin sees delete button', ({ adminUser }) => {
  expect(adminUser.role).toBe('admin')
})$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
