INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '70218477-4be0-43c1-9143-51aa2662e6cf',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$vitest + Storybook — Story play() Functions as Native Browser Tests$escape$,
  $escape$Storybook's `@storybook/addon-vitest` plugin turns every `.stories.tsx` file into a vitest test suite with zero extra boilerplate. Add `storybookTest()` to `vitest.config.ts`, point vitest at a Playwright browser provider, and each named story export becomes a discrete test case automatically.

The lever is the `play` function. Authored with `@storybook/test` — which re-exports `userEvent` and `expect` directly from vitest — play functions run inside a real Chromium tab during `vitest run`. Your `SubmitsForm` story's interaction sequence is now a browser-mode vitest test. Same assertion API, no duplication, CI-ready.

For jsdom-level tests, `composeStories()` from `@storybook/react` imports stories as fully-decorated components. Wrap them in `@testing-library/react`'s `render()` and assert with vitest's `expect` — all decorators, args, and context applied automatically.

The payoff: every UI state you document in a story is a regression test. Write the error-state story, add a `play` function — vitest catches the break in CI before review. Story-driven development stops being documentation theater and becomes your actual test coverage.$escape$,
  $escape$// vitest.config.ts
import { storybookTest } from '@storybook/addon-vitest/vitest-plugin';
export default defineConfig({
  plugins: [storybookTest()],
  test: {
    browser: { provider: 'playwright', name: 'chromium', enabled: true },
    setupFiles: ['.storybook/vitest.setup.ts'],
  },
});

// Button.stories.tsx — play() becomes a vitest browser test
export const SubmitsForm: Story = {
  play: async ({ canvasElement }) => {
    const canvas = within(canvasElement);
    await userEvent.click(canvas.getByRole('button', { name: /submit/i }));
    await expect(canvas.getByText('Submitted!')).toBeInTheDocument();
  },
};$escape$,
